column86:
City of Playford



Population growth context

Playford’s population is projected to increase from ~100,000 in 2021 to over 140,000 by 2041 – a ~40% rise.
Growth is concentrated in new housing estates at Munno Para, Angle Vale, Buckland Park, and Virginia.
Playford is one of SA’s fastest growing LGAs, driven by affordability, proximity to Adelaide, and planned master-planned estates.
Residential

$3.4 billion Riverlea development – 12,000 new homes and 40,000 residents; construction under way, expected to take 30 years.
$1 billion Buckland Park expansion – residential growth corridor, staging 10,000+ new homes.
$200 million Angle Vale growth precinct – mixed residential lots with supporting retail/amenities.
Industrial

Edinburgh Defence Precinct expansion – national defence hub, home to major primes and SMEs, generating thousands of skilled jobs.
Playford Alive industrial estates – targeted manufacturing and logistics growth precincts.
Northern Adelaide Food Park – food processing hub supporting long-term jobs and supply chain growth.
Commercial and civic

Elizabeth City Centre redevelopment – staged upgrades to retail and services, supporting Playford’s role as the north’s commercial hub.
Playford CBD master plan – council-led civic, retail, and commercial expansion with new plazas, transport links, and health/education services.
Health and education

Lyell McEwin Hospital upgrades – significant expansion of services for northern Adelaide.
New Playford Health Hub – integrated health and allied services precinct.
Tertiary education investments – UniSA Mawson Lakes and TAFE SA expansions to support local training.
Transport

Northern Connector / North-South Corridor – major arterial road project improving freight and commuter access.
Adelaide–Gawler Rail Electrification (completed 2022) – modernised service, reduced commute times, increased service frequency.
New road upgrades – Angle Vale Road and Curtis Road duplications improving access to new estates.
Job implications

Defence precinct growth to underpin long-term, high-value skilled employment.
Food manufacturing and processing hub forecast to generate thousands of direct and indirect jobs.
Ongoing residential construction to sustain significant trade and service-based employment.

Playford’s population is projected to increase from ~100,000 in 2021 to over 140,000 by 2041 – a ~40% rise.
Growth is concentrated in new housing estates at Munno Para, Angle Vale, Buckland Park, and Virginia.
Playford is one of SA’s fastest growing LGAs, driven by affordability, proximity to Adelaide, and planned master-planned estates.
Residential

$3.4 billion Riverlea development – 12,000 new homes and 40,000 residents; construction under way, expected to take 30 years.
$1 billion Buckland Park expansion – residential growth corridor, staging 10,000+ new homes.
$200 million Angle Vale growth precinct – mixed residential lots with supporting retail/amenities.
Industrial

Edinburgh Defence Precinct expansion – national defence hub, home to major primes and SMEs, generating thousands of skilled jobs.
Playford Alive industrial estates – targeted manufacturing and logistics growth precincts.
Northern Adelaide Food Park – food processing hub supporting long-term jobs and supply chain growth.
Commercial and civic

Elizabeth City Centre redevelopment – staged upgrades to retail and services, supporting Playford’s role as the north’s commercial hub.
Playford CBD master plan – council-led civic, retail, and commercial expansion with new plazas, transport links, and health/education services.
Health and education

Lyell McEwin Hospital upgrades – significant expansion of services for northern Adelaide.
New Playford Health Hub – integrated health and allied services precinct.
Tertiary education investments – UniSA Mawson Lakes and TAFE SA expansions to support local training.
Transport

Northern Connector / North-South Corridor – major arterial road project improving freight and commuter access.
Adelaide–Gawler Rail Electrification (completed 2022) – modernised service, reduced commute times, increased service frequency.
New road upgrades – Angle Vale Road and Curtis Road duplications improving access to new estates.
Job implications

Defence precinct growth to underpin long-term, high-value skilled employment.
Food manufacturing and processing hub forecast to generate thousands of direct and indirect jobs.
Ongoing residential construction to sustain significant trade and service-based employment.

City of Playford



Population growth context

Playford’s population is projected to increase from ~100,000 in 2021 to over 140,000 by 2041 – a ~40% rise.
Growth is concentrated in new housing estates at Munno Para, Angle Vale, Buckland Park, and Virginia.
Playford is one of SA’s fastest growing LGAs, driven by affordability, proximity to Adelaide, and planned master-planned estates.
Residential

$3.4 billion Riverlea development – 12,000 new homes and 40,000 residents; construction under way, expected to take 30 years.
$1 billion Buckland Park expansion – residential growth corridor, staging 10,000+ new homes.
$200 million Angle Vale growth precinct – mixed residential lots with supporting retail/amenities.
Industrial

Edinburgh Defence Precinct expansion – national defence hub, home to major primes and SMEs, generating thousands of skilled jobs.
Playford Alive industrial estates – targeted manufacturing and logistics growth precincts.
Northern Adelaide Food Park – food processing hub supporting long-term jobs and supply chain growth.
Commercial and civic

Elizabeth City Centre redevelopment – staged upgrades to retail and services, supporting Playford’s role as the north’s commercial hub.
Playford CBD master plan – council-led civic, retail, and commercial expansion with new plazas, transport links, and health/education services.
Health and education

Lyell McEwin Hospital upgrades – significant expansion of services for northern Adelaide.
New Playford Health Hub – integrated health and allied services precinct.
Tertiary education investments – UniSA Mawson Lakes and TAFE SA expansions to support local training.
Transport

Northern Connector / North-South Corridor – major arterial road project improving freight and commuter access.
Adelaide–Gawler Rail Electrification (completed 2022) – modernised service, reduced commute times, increased service frequency.
New road upgrades – Angle Vale Road and Curtis Road duplications improving access to new estates.
Job implications

Defence precinct growth to underpin long-term, high-value skilled employment.
Food manufacturing and processing hub forecast to generate thousands of direct and indirect jobs.
Ongoing residential construction to sustain significant trade and service-based employment.",0.72"

Growth location – Davoren Park sits within the high-growth City of Playford, one of South Australia’s fastest developing regions, supported by strong infrastructure and population growth forecasts.
Security of Torrens Title – No ongoing strata fees, improving net investor returns.
Future value uplift potential – New build completion (September 2025 registration) positions these dwellings to benefit from continued demand in Adelaide’s northern corridor.

column86:
City of Playford



Population growth context

Playford’s population is projected to increase from ~100,000 in 2021 to over 140,000 by 2041 – a ~40% rise.
Growth is concentrated in new housing estates at Munno Para, Angle Vale, Buckland Park, and Virginia.
Playford is one of SA’s fastest growing LGAs, driven by affordability, proximity to Adelaide, and planned master-planned estates.
Residential

$3.4 billion Riverlea development – 12,000 new homes and 40,000 residents; construction under way, expected to take 30 years.
$1 billion Buckland Park expansion – residential growth corridor, staging 10,000+ new homes.
$200 million Angle Vale growth precinct – mixed residential lots with supporting retail/amenities.
Industrial

Edinburgh Defence Precinct expansion – national defence hub, home to major primes and SMEs, generating thousands of skilled jobs.
Playford Alive industrial estates – targeted manufacturing and logistics growth precincts.
Northern Adelaide Food Park – food processing hub supporting long-term jobs and supply chain growth.
Commercial and civic

Elizabeth City Centre redevelopment – staged upgrades to retail and services, supporting Playford’s role as the north’s commercial hub.
Playford CBD master plan – council-led civic, retail, and commercial expansion with new plazas, transport links, and health/education services.
Health and education

Lyell McEwin Hospital upgrades – significant expansion of services for northern Adelaide.
New Playford Health Hub – integrated health and allied services precinct.
Tertiary education investments – UniSA Mawson Lakes and TAFE SA expansions to support local training.
Transport

Northern Connector / North-South Corridor – major arterial road project improving freight and commuter access.
Adelaide–Gawler Rail Electrification (completed 2022) – modernised service, reduced commute times, increased service frequency.
New road upgrades – Angle Vale Road and Curtis Road duplications improving access to new estates.
Job implications

Defence precinct growth to underpin long-term, high-value skilled employment.
Food manufacturing and processing hub forecast to generate thousands of direct and indirect jobs.
Ongoing residential construction to sustain significant trade and service-based employment.

Attractive Rental Yields - Tight vacancy rates in the Dapto–Avondale corridor mean rental returns are above regional averages, offering appealing yields for investors.
Low Vacancy and High Tenant Demand - Proximity to employment hubs in Wollongong and Port Kembla, plus quality local schools, makes the area a consistent draw for tenants.
Major Infrastructure Connections - Easy access to the M1 Princes Motorway, Dapto Train Station, and bus links to Wollongong and Sydney improves connectivity and lifestyle appeal.
Lifestyle and Amenity Rich Location - Close to Dapto Mall, local cafes, parks, and the Illawarra Escarpment, Avoca Park combines urban convenience with natural beauty.
Affordability Compared to Sydney Metro - Entry prices are significantly lower than comparable Sydney properties, attracting both first home buyers and investors seeking value.
Proximity to Beaches and Coastal Living - Port Kembla Beach and Lake Illawarra are within short driving distance, adding to the area’s appeal for lifestyle-focused individuals and families.

Wollongong City

Population growth context

Wollongong's population is forecast to grow from 215,500 in 2021 to 270,500 by 2041, an increase of 55,000 people or 26% driven by affordability, lifestyle appeal, health and education sectors, and transport-oriented developments. The West Dapto Urban Release Area alone is expected to accommodate 59,000 people and 19,500 dwellings over the long term.
Residential

$600 million The Works redevelopment to deliver 550 homes on 18ha in Corrimal with shops and parklands
$520 million Cascadia by Sekisui House to create 455 lots over 36ha in Calderwood, with first release in 2025
$278 million Forest Reach masterplanned estate in Huntley to deliver 648 lots (sold by Stockland to Avid)
$150 million 150-unit development at former Dapto Primary School site by Community Housing Trust
$143 million Five Islands mixed-use project with five apartment towers (DA lodged August 2024)
Cost to be determined 1,300-home Warrawong Plaza redevelopment including 15% affordable housing, first delivery by 2028
Cost to be determined Gwynneville rezoning to enable 1,250 dwellings (50% social and affordable housing)
Cost to be determined 906-apartment transit-oriented project at former Bunnings site near Wollongong Station
Industrial

$1.15 billion BlueScope steelworks blast furnace upgrade to secure supply and support 300 construction jobs
Cost to be determined BlueScope Master Plan for 200ha multi-industrial precinct expected to generate 30,000 jobs over time
$130 million Jemena Port Kembla Lateral Looping Project to deliver 7.8km gas pipeline and expand Kembla Grange facility
Commercial and civic

$229 million The Globe project to include a 15-storey hotel, office space, club and motel (Wollongong CBD)
$80 million Atchison & Kenny twin tower project to add 262 apartments and ground-floor activation
Cost to be determined Easterly Wollongong project to deliver 21 apartments and two retail spaces
Health and education

$1 billion Illawarra International Health Precinct in West Dapto to be developed over eight stages
$780 million New Shellharbour Hospital with expanded emergency, elective surgery, and mental health services
$250 million Stage 1 of UOW Health & Wellbeing Precinct to deliver aged care and retirement living at Fairy Meadow
$200 million Expansion of Wollongong Private Hospital to include ED, ICU, oncology and more beds
$21.9 million Planning and design work underway for future Wollongong Hospital redevelopment
Cost to be determined New community health centre in Warrawong and expanded Wollongong Hospital rehab services

Population projected to grow from ~210,000 (2021) to 370,000 by 2041 – a 76% increase.

Strong Tenant Demand - A solid population of FIFO workers, industrial employees, and young families ensures a diverse and stable tenant pool.
Improved Transport Connectivity - The proximity to the Bruce Highway, Gladstone Airport, and regional rail services makes the suburb well-connected to broader Queensland and interstate destinations.

Gladstone Regional Council
Population growth context
Gladstone's population is forecast to increase from 63,500 in 2021 to 78,485 by 2046, an uplift of 14,985 people or 24%. This growth is driven by surging industrial investment, renewable energy infrastructure, and economic diversification efforts. The city supports over 28,000 jobs with strong representation in manufacturing and construction sectors, complemented by affordability and a high quality coastal lifestyle.
Residential
$170 million Riverbend Retirement Village under construction at Agnes Water to deliver 190 gated homes with premium amenities
$180 million Solana Lifestyle Resort delivering 201 homes across 5 stages with community facilities at Agnes Water
$90 million Retirement village planned in West Gladstone with 196 dwellings and four commercial tenancies
$100 million Tannum Blue Estate delivering 186 homes in green-certified development
Cost to be determined Beecher Estate under construction with 350 acreage lots across 2,000 acres near Dawson Highway
Cost to be determined 14-storey, 40-unit apartment project proposed in Central Lane, Gladstone CBD
Cost to be determined Former serviced apartments converted into 33 social housing units by State Government
Industrial
$4.7 billion Gladstone Energy and Ammonia Project to convert coal into ammonia, gas and electricity from 2026
$45 million Regional Industrial Land Improvement Program to deliver enabling infrastructure across Gladstone
Cost to be determined Rio Tinto renewable power purchase deals to supply 2.2GW to support smelter operations until 2040
Cost to be determined Rio Tinto and Sumitomo $111 million hydrogen calcination trial to reduce alumina emissions
Commercial and civic
$14.1 million Council’s 2025–26 capital works program includes upgrades to roads, water, wastewater, parks and bridges
Cost to be determined Boyne Tannum Aquatic Recreation Centre approved with 50m pool, cafe, gym, relocated in 2024
Cost to be determined Hervey Road Sports Precinct redevelopment proposed to increase capacity to 10,000 spectators
Health and education
$42 million Expansion of Gladstone Hospital completed in 2020, including new emergency and outpatient departments
Cost to be determined Hospital West Wing opened in 2023 with three surgical theatres via Mater Hospital refurbishment
Cost to be determined Strong presence of public/private K–12 schools, two CQUniversity campuses and TAFE Queensland
Transport
$31.4 billion Inland Rail Link with business case underway for Toowoomba–Gladstone extension to unlock $15 billion in investment
$983 million Fitzroy to Gladstone Pipeline under construction to deliver 30,000ML/year by 2026
Job implications (construction + ongoing)
~10,000 jobs potential from Inland Rail Toowoomba–Gladstone extension during construction and post-completion investment
~9,000 jobs expected from CQ-H2 Hydrogen Project if fully funded, generating $8.9 billion in economic output
~400 jobs Port of Gladstone channel duplication to expand container capacity and cold storage logistics
~300 construction, 120 ongoing jobs from Alpha HPA Stage 2 alumina refinery producing tech-grade materials
~200 jobs during construction of Fitzroy–Gladstone water pipeline

Population growth context
Gladstone's population is forecast to increase from 63,500 in 2021 to 78,485 by 2046, an uplift of 14,985 people or 24%. This growth is driven by surging industrial investment, renewable energy infrastructure, and economic diversification efforts. The city supports over 28,000 jobs with strong representation in manufacturing and construction sectors, complemented by affordability and a high quality coastal lifestyle.

$4.7 billion Gladstone Energy and Ammonia Project to convert coal into ammonia, gas and electricity from 2026

Cost to be determined Rio Tinto renewable power purchase deals to supply 2.2GW to support smelter operations until 2040
Cost to be determined Rio Tinto and Sumitomo $111 million hydrogen calcination trial to reduce alumina emissions
Commercial and civic
$14.1 million Council’s 2025–26 capital works program includes upgrades to roads, water, wastewater, parks and bridges

$42 million Expansion of Gladstone Hospital completed in 2020, including new emergency and outpatient departments

Cost to be determined Strong presence of public/private K–12 schools, two CQUniversity campuses and TAFE Queensland
Transport
$31.4 billion Inland Rail Link with business case underway for Toowoomba–Gladstone extension to unlock $15 billion in investment
$983 million Fitzroy to Gladstone Pipeline under construction to deliver 30,000ML/year by 2026

~10,000 jobs potential from Inland Rail Toowoomba–Gladstone extension during construction and post-completion investment

~200 jobs during construction of Fitzroy–Gladstone water pipeline

Strong Capital Growth Potential - Eli Waters is part of the Fraser Coast LGA, which has seen consistent median house price growth, supported by increased regional migration and government investment.
Healthy Rental Yields - Rental yields in Eli Waters average around 5.2%, offering strong income potential for investors compared to metro averages.
Low Vacancy Rates - Vacancy rates in Eli Waters remain below 1.5%, reflecting strong tenant demand and limited rental supply.
Major Infrastructure Investment - The Fraser Coast region benefits from ongoing infrastructure upgrades, including the $40 million redevelopment of Hervey Bay Hospital and road network improvements.
Affordability Driving Migration - With median house prices significantly lower than Brisbane, Eli Waters continues to attract both owner-occupiers and investors seeking affordability.
Excellent Transport Links - Close proximity to Hervey Bay Airport and major roads offers convenient transport access for residents and visitors alike.
High Tenant Demand - The area appeals to a mix of retirees, families, and healthcare workers, with strong demand for quality rental properties near hospitals and schools.

Fraser Coast Regional Council
Population growth context
Fraser Coast's population has grown from 101,504 in 2016 to 151,070 projected by 2046, an increase of nearly 50%. This surge is driven by lifestyle affordability, strong internal migration, job creation in health, manufacturing, and tourism sectors, and rising development activity. Hervey Bay and Maryborough anchor the region, supported by continued land releases and housing development.
